lenders.occupational_info:
Well, actually believe it or not, I am disabled, I collect retirement/social security. I spend alot of time at home because of this, so I have aquired a hobby/entrepreneur business within a virtual world online game. I design clothing, shoes, hair, skins & shapes for the characters in the game. SecondLife is a virtual world based off of real life but with ways to expand your dreams, fantasies, role playing, business dreams. Pretty much, anything you can do in reality in the world, you can do in SecondLife. Run a business(any business, build and sell your designs, own and run a dance club, become a Model, go skydiving, its endless. Its not just a game, but an enhancement to reality for a hobby or a real business that makes profits within the game, which you can, if you make enough in-world, transfer those funds to real money. 
So, yeah.. I think of my SecondLife Business as a Real Life Business.
I am very passionate about it, love meeting different people from around the world, my friends I make there, I consider friends that would live near me. Its not about the profit really, its about the experience. Though, I haven't made enough money in-world to transfer to real money but I am having a blast. It also, believe it or not, SecondLife helps some of my disabilities, some times. 
I am hoping one day my business in-world will make me a profit in reality! :)
“Dream as if you'll live forever, Live as if you'll die today.”

lenders.name: High Meadows School
lenders.loan_because:
Voices of the students:
We lend to KIVA because it’s basically making a small business wealthy and big for free.
 KIVA is a good organization because we are lending to people in need so they can provide for their families.
 It felt good helping someone who wanted to start their own business.
 We want to make the world a better place. It’s just one person at a time, but it still helps.
 You already want to help people in poorer countries, and KIVA is a safe, effective way to loan them money.
 We wanted to help the entrepreneurs with stuff for their businesses and their families and health.
 It’s like, if you were put in that position, you would want people to lend to you.
We wanted to change someone’s life to make it better.
We each have an opportunity to live a life.
 I think it really helps the world every time you loan.
 Sometimes we misuse money, and instead of misusing money, we could give it to someone who really needs it.
 It not only helps their family, but it helps the people they sell their products to.
Thinking about the people…here at High Meadows, we have more money than the people there. We have things they would never dream of.  They need shoes, shelter; we just keep on buying and buying.
 Because we’re environmentally friendly, we should be people-friendly, too.  We made a ton of money to help through the fundraiser.
We want to help people make money and feed their families.
We’re helping people in need.  We already have everything that we need and we have money to afford the things we’ll need later on.  So why not use that money to help someone else.
 It feels good to lend.  I think just one loan could help…change a sad life into a happy life.
 We can help everyday people start a big business so that they can get the money that they need.
 KIVA is a safe website and good place to lend to.  It can change people’s lives.
lenders.occupational_info: These students are in a multi-age 4th and 5th grade class at High Meadows School.  They became interested in KIVA through their Environmental Studies teacher, Chris Robie, and with the help of their classroom teachers, Gary Denning and Jean Hunter, put on a Talent Show to raise money to lend.  In 2013 a second talent show was held as a younger generation of students wanted to help.  We have been able to find great ways to tie Kiva loans to our curriculum such as geography studies (e.g. loans in Africa), examining health and housing needs around the world and even talking about banking and credit.  As a result, we have decided to include all of the 4th & 5th grade classrooms in to our lending activities.
